<TITLE> Lift emergency for meaningful polls: Hasina </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 London, Oct 10 (bdnews24.com)  Awami League president Sheikh Hasina said the state of emergency needs to be lifted if the nation is to have a meaningful election. "The emergency has to be lifted so that the candidates can do election publicity and voters can cast their ballots in favour of the candidate of their choice without intimidation. No meaningful election is possible under emergency." She made the demand at a seminar titled "Bangladesh: Future of Democracy and Human Rights" at the House of Lords auditorium in London on Thursday. "Development of the country is not possible without election. An elected government only can solve all the problems of the country. "So all hope that the election will be held on December 18 as per the EC roadmap. However, if the state of emergency remains in force there will be a doubt regarding election. Vice chair of the UK Parliamentary Human Rights Group and chairman of International Bangladesh Foundation Lord Avebury MacDonald MP, Jeremy Corbin MP, Steve Pound MP, baroness Paula Uddin, Lord Dholakia,, Human Rights Watch South Asia Affairs director Brad Adams, UK BNP president Kamaruddin Ahmed, UK Awami League advisory council chairman Sultan Sharif and Mohila AL leader Rahima Akhter also spoke. Hasina urged the British parliament members to play their role in creating congenial atmosphere for next national election in Bangladesh and send observers to watch the gegenel elections slated for Dec. 18. "I am an optimist. Whenever I got an opportunity I tried to bring smiles to the faces of the people of my country." The former prime minister listed the developments and progresses the country made under her 1996-2001 administration. She called fir withdrawal of the cases filed against the party leaders and workers and restoration of democratic rule for making Bangladesh a middle income country by 2020. bdne
